{
  "id": "019d286a-f2d7-7750-81b8-3279cdfcca8d",
  "content": "# M3.2: RAG Pipeline Design\n\n## Summary\n\nAdd a trait-based RAG pipeline to `corvia-kernel` that standardizes all retrieval, context assembly, and generation through a single orchestrated path. Three pluggable stages — `Retriever`, `Augmenter`, `GenerationEngine` — enable strategy benchmarking and future adaptation. Two modes: `context()` (retrieve + augment) and `ask()` (retrieve + augment + generate).\n\n\n## Motivation\n\n1. **No RAG today.** Corvia has strong vector retrieval but no context assembly or answer generation. MCP `corvia_search` returns raw results — agents must interpret them alone.\n\n2. **REST/MCP bypass ContextBuilder.** Both `rest.rs:search_memories` and `mcp.rs:corvia_search` call `store.search()` directly, skipping RBAC and visibility filtering. This is a correctness bug.\n\n3. **Graph+vector is the differentiator.** Commodity vector search is everywhere (Pinecone, pgvector, built-in IDE memory). Corvia's moat is organizational graph relationships + git-truth + temporal awareness. The RAG pipeline must combine vector similarity with graph traversal.\n\n4. **Benchmarking readiness.** The industry moves fast. Trait-based stages let M6 eval swap in different retrieval/augmentation strategies and measure precision@k, MRR, NDCG without code changes.\n",
  "source_version": "docs/rfcs/2026-03-02-m3.2-rag-pipeline-design.md",
